<p><div class="speaker">Unidentified participant</div>Sir, one of the most interesting aspects of "The Bear," to me, is the
                    conflict between man and the wilderness. I would like to ask you if you intend for
                    the reader to sympathize more with Old Ben and his conflict with hunters or with
                    the hunters and their conflict with Old Ben?</p>
<p><div class="speaker">William Faulkner</div>Well, not sympathize. I&mdash;I doubt if&mdash;if
                    the&mdash;the writer is asking anyone to sympathize, to choose sides. That
                    is the reader's right. What the writer is asking is compassion, understanding
                    that&mdash;that change must alter, must happen, and change is going to alter
                    what was. That no matter how fine anything seems, it can't endure because
                    it&mdash;once it stops&mdash;abandons motion, it is dead. It's to have
                    compassion for the&mdash;for the anguish that&mdash;that the wilderness
                    itself may have felt by being ruthlessly destroyed by axes, by&mdash;by men
                    who simply wanted to&mdash;to make that earth grow something that
                        they could sell for a profit, which brought into it a
                    condition based on an evil like human bondage. It's not to&mdash;to choose
                    sides at all, just to compassionate the&mdash;the&mdash;the good,
                    splendid things which change must destroy, the splendid, fine things which are a
                    part of man's past, too, part of man's heritage, too. But they were obsolete and
                    had to go. But that's no need to&mdash;to not feel compassion for
                    them, simply because they were obsolete.
                </p>
</div>
